00:06:58,744 --> 00:07:04,909
We have a lot of these in-jokes, a lot of this lore that we chat about and talk about,

88
00:07:05,790 --> 00:07:08,513
and for me that's a massive part of our studio culture.

89
00:07:09,516 --> 00:07:16,203
So our studio culture is what I think the best studio culture I've ever experienced in a workplace.

90
00:07:16,904 --> 00:07:19,146
And there's a bunch of reasons why that's the case.

91
00:07:19,226 --> 00:07:23,410
And it's a really conscious choice from studio leadership to get it to that state.

92
00:07:24,952 --> 00:07:31,839
And so if you're looking to try and either improve or kind of start a studio and create a culture.

93
00:07:32,848 --> 00:07:35,428
There's some really key steps that you should follow, right?

94
00:07:35,489 --> 00:07:37,309
So you need to start with your goal.

95
00:07:37,489 --> 00:07:40,290
You need to work out what it is that you actually want to achieve

96
00:07:40,430 --> 00:07:41,610
with the culture of your studio.

97
00:07:43,010 --> 00:07:45,131
Then you need to ask yourselves how you achieve that.

98
00:07:45,891 --> 00:07:47,151
So you need actionable steps.

99
00:07:47,351 --> 00:07:50,532
You can't just say, oh, I want our studio culture to be fun

100
00:07:50,892 --> 00:07:54,593
or inclusive or relaxed or flexible.

101
00:07:54,893 --> 00:07:58,154
You need to actively think about what you're going to do

102
00:07:58,234 --> 00:07:59,675
to achieve that as step two.

103
00:08:00,820 --> 00:08:02,603
Then you need to make a commitment to those actions.

104
00:08:03,003 --> 00:08:04,125
You need to commit as a team.

105
00:08:04,145 --> 00:08:05,767
You need to write it down.

106
00:08:05,787 --> 00:08:09,673
You need to explain and transparently share with your team what you're trying to do.

107
00:08:10,434 --> 00:08:13,938
Make that commitment publicly and within your team.

108
00:08:13,958 --> 00:08:16,922
And make it really clear that that is what you're trying to do.

109
00:08:18,182 --> 00:08:21,242
You need to learn from any mistakes you make because it won't be perfect.

110
00:08:21,702 --> 00:08:23,943
You won't just wake up one day and be like,

111
00:08:24,063 --> 00:08:26,724
ah, it's exactly what we asked for. It's exactly what we were planning.

112
00:08:27,704 --> 00:08:31,545
So whatever mistakes are made, you need to listen, learn from those,

113
00:08:31,905 --> 00:08:35,406
and grow from that and create new commitments as a result of that.

114
00:08:37,006 --> 00:08:39,367
And lastly, you need to remember the job's never done.

115
00:08:40,127 --> 00:08:43,508
It's not like we have a fantastic studio culture at Sledgehammer

116
00:08:43,548 --> 00:08:45,228
and we've said great, let's just.

117
00:08:47,212 --> 00:08:51,335
Mark that off as done and put that over there and then get on with something else.

118
00:08:52,615 --> 00:08:56,418
The work that is involved in creating studio culture is really important

119
00:08:56,978 --> 00:08:58,720
and we have to kind of keep maintaining that.

120
00:09:01,802 --> 00:09:09,547
Cool, so there are kind of a bunch of different values that we use to explain and explore our

121
00:09:09,767 --> 00:09:13,770
studio culture and come up with the different kind of actions that we want to take as part of that.

122
00:09:15,242 --> 00:09:17,023
So all of these are on our website.

123
00:09:17,063 --> 00:09:19,185
They're also given to all of our new employees

124
00:09:19,245 --> 00:09:20,386
as soon as they join the team.

125
00:09:21,446 --> 00:09:23,888
And they are designed to kind of guide us

126
00:09:24,008 --> 00:09:25,189
in the direction that we want to go.

127
00:09:26,490 --> 00:09:28,832
So we want to cultivate greatness in our team.

128
00:09:29,712 --> 00:09:31,273
So make sure that they have an environment

129
00:09:31,333 --> 00:09:33,935
where they can all thrive and do their very best.

130
00:09:35,316 --> 00:09:36,857
We want to empower every single person

131
00:09:36,937 --> 00:09:38,638
on our team to be a game maker.

132
00:09:38,658 --> 00:09:40,119
So no matter where they are,

133
00:09:40,259 --> 00:09:41,480
we want to empower them to

134
00:09:42,086 --> 00:09:45,450
have an input and have a say in what our game looks like.

135
00:09:47,513 --> 00:09:51,858
We want everybody to feel like they're empowered to innovate and change and do

136
00:09:52,098 --> 00:09:57,304
new and interesting things. We don't want to be following the trends, we want to be making the trends.

137
00:09:58,878 --> 00:10:00,859
We want to give people the space to fail and grow.

138
00:10:00,879 --> 00:10:04,641
So this goes back to what I was saying before about if you make mistakes,

139
00:10:04,722 --> 00:10:06,403
making sure that you learn from them.

140
00:10:07,123 --> 00:10:10,805
Um, we want our team to know that making a mistake is not the end of the world.

141
00:10:10,985 --> 00:10:11,966
Everyone makes mistakes.

142
00:10:12,767 --> 00:10:16,749
Uh, and we want them to know that we encourage them to grow from that and,

143
00:10:16,929 --> 00:10:20,792
and learn from those mistakes and never feel like they are, you know, in

144
00:10:20,852 --> 00:10:22,653
trouble for doing something wrong.

145
00:10:24,666 --> 00:10:28,291
We want to make everyone feel like they're a builder, like they're creating something.

146
00:10:28,312 --> 00:10:31,977
They're creating an amazing team, they're creating amazing games.

147
00:10:33,379 --> 00:10:36,845
We're kind of working together to build something amazing together.

148
00:10:38,626 --> 00:10:40,487
We want to be open, honest and transparent.

149
00:10:40,907 --> 00:10:42,788
And this one's really, really, really important to us.

150
00:10:43,388 --> 00:10:46,410
Obviously, they all are, but this one is, you know,

151
00:10:46,430 --> 00:10:50,573
we hear this kind of talked about in internal communication all the time.

152
00:10:50,593 --> 00:10:54,735
You know, we're always trying to tell the team what's going on,

153
00:10:54,875 --> 00:10:56,617
even if we don't have the whole story yet,

154
00:10:56,977 --> 00:10:59,418
just to make sure people don't feel like we're hiding anything,

155
00:10:59,498 --> 00:11:02,500
that, you know, a bunch of conversations are happening behind closed doors.

156
00:11:04,323 --> 00:11:06,324
And we are an actions over words studio.

157
00:11:07,424 --> 00:11:10,785
And this is particularly important for things like diversity and inclusivity.

158
00:11:11,586 --> 00:11:18,648
We don't just say the things, we don't just, you know, make our profile picture rainbow coloured during Pride Month.

159
00:11:19,148 --> 00:11:26,231
We do a lot of work to back that up, both internally inside our studio and also externally with our community.

160
00:11:27,251 --> 00:11:29,072
So these are the studio values that guide us.

161
00:11:30,728 --> 00:11:35,052
And kind of what we've done from there is figure out what that actually kind of means, right?

162
00:11:35,072 --> 00:11:38,214
So it's not just about, okay, great, you're a game maker.

163
00:11:38,314 --> 00:11:43,759
It's about actively seeking feedback on our games from everybody, no matter which department they're in.

164
00:11:44,659 --> 00:11:47,421
And we explain this to ourselves and we explain this to our team.

165
00:11:48,904 --> 00:11:52,866
Um, we, yeah, like I, like I kind of already said, we make sure we have a safe

166
00:11:52,906 --> 00:11:56,108
environment to make mistakes and we don't keep secrets.

167
00:11:56,308 --> 00:12:00,590
We make sure people know what we know and also know if we can't

168
00:12:00,630 --> 00:12:01,831
tell them something yet and why.

169
00:12:01,851 --> 00:12:04,372
We try to be as honest about all of that as we can.

170
00:12:06,854 --> 00:12:09,495
But remember how I said, we need to do more than just have a goal.

171
00:12:09,535 --> 00:12:12,877
We need to have the actions in place that we're going to take to reach that goal.

172
00:12:14,131 --> 00:12:20,537
So these are some of the actions we take to achieve these handful of values that I've just kind of pulled out as examples.

173
00:12:21,457 --> 00:12:26,301
So for getting feedback from everybody, we do daily play tests with the entire team.

174
00:12:26,542 --> 00:12:27,222
Everyone's welcome.

175
00:12:27,623 --> 00:12:28,583
Everyone can give feedback.

176
00:12:29,144 --> 00:12:32,307
Everyone can play the game that we're working on throughout the year as well.

177
00:12:32,387 --> 00:12:37,591
And just kind of say whatever, give our feedback to the right people anytime.

178
00:12:37,631 --> 00:12:39,973
But we have dedicated play test periods for that as well.

179
00:12:41,519 --> 00:12:44,967
We have feedback channels that people can use on Slack via email.

180
00:12:45,528 --> 00:12:47,573
We make sure everyone knows the right people to talk to.

181
00:12:47,653 --> 00:12:50,880
If they do have something they want to share, we kind of open as

182
00:12:50,900 --> 00:12:52,163
many feedback channels as we can.

183
00:12:54,565 --> 00:12:57,347
For Fail and Grow, we share stories about our mistakes.

184
00:12:57,587 --> 00:12:58,248
We don't hide them.

185
00:12:58,408 --> 00:13:00,349
We don't pretend that we're perfect.

186
00:13:00,709 --> 00:13:03,771
And that goes for leadership, not just people

187
00:13:03,791 --> 00:13:06,073
who are on the team and making our game on the ground.

188
00:13:06,633 --> 00:13:08,715
Leadership talks about their mistakes as well.

189
00:13:08,795 --> 00:13:10,436
We talk about silly things that we've done

190
00:13:10,536 --> 00:13:13,618
and what we learned from it, both in this studio

191
00:13:13,698 --> 00:13:15,579
and in previous studios throughout our careers.

192
00:13:16,740 --> 00:13:18,821
That's a really important part of making people feel

193
00:13:18,841 --> 00:13:20,262
like they're safe to make mistakes,

194
00:13:20,883 --> 00:13:22,464
that everyone's made mistakes

195
00:13:22,544 --> 00:13:23,645
and this is what we got out of it.

196
00:13:24,854 --> 00:13:26,936
We never call someone out for failing and learning.

197
00:13:27,416 --> 00:13:31,500
You know, if someone made a mistake and failed, we never, you know, call them out for it.

198
00:13:31,520 --> 00:13:32,881
We never embarrass them for it.

199
00:13:32,921 --> 00:13:37,224
We always make sure that people feel like they know they can grow and learn from that mistake.

200
00:13:37,264 --> 00:13:38,305
And we empower them to do that.

201
00:13:38,345 --> 00:13:41,428
We help them with what that looks like and what those steps are.

202
00:13:43,689 --> 00:13:50,533
In terms of this open, honest and transparent, we have fortnightly Q&As with our studio leadership team.

203
00:13:50,593 --> 00:13:58,877
So our studio head and our COO jump in a Slack channel, we have a form that we can use to send in questions, and they will answer whatever questions our team has.

204
00:13:59,217 --> 00:14:00,858
Sometimes they're silly, sometimes they're serious.

205
00:14:02,639 --> 00:14:13,405
It's usually somewhere in between and we kind of have that forum as a regular opportunity for people to hear open, honest and transparent feedback from studio leadership.

206
00:14:14,926 --> 00:14:24,352
And we also have like a lot of jokes and informal chats and that comes back to what I said originally about our culture that we have a really fun and an open culture at Sledgehammer.

207
00:14:25,352 --> 00:14:30,255
And these sorts of jokes and informal chats create this approachability with our leadership team.

208
00:14:31,314 --> 00:14:40,238
So they aren't just kind of sitting over there in their ivory tower when no one is kind of scared to talk to them because they're really relaxed and fun and silly.

209
00:14:40,258 --> 00:14:47,582
And that's a really important part of how we kind of create this transparency and openness in our culture.

210
00:14:50,832 --> 00:14:53,373
So all of that is all well and good in terms of our plan,

211
00:14:54,433 --> 00:14:57,514
but I also just had a chat with some people on our team about what

212
00:14:58,214 --> 00:15:02,956
they like about our studio culture. And this can be a really good check-in for

213
00:15:03,476 --> 00:15:06,677
figuring out what it is you want to maintain in your studio.

214
00:15:07,077 --> 00:15:10,398
So if you ask your team, hey what do you like about our studio culture currently,

215
00:15:10,698 --> 00:15:13,199
what don't you like, this can be a really good way of

216
00:15:14,039 --> 00:15:17,721
knowing what they value and then kind of trying to figure out how you've

217
00:15:17,781 --> 00:15:18,601
cultivated that.

218
00:15:19,181 --> 00:15:24,706
And what you can keep doing to create a positive culture for your team.

219
00:15:24,726 --> 00:15:29,730
So some of the callouts people had was that were inclusive, that no one has an ego,

220
00:15:30,071 --> 00:15:32,813
and I think that was probably the one that was called out the most.

221
00:15:34,094 --> 00:15:37,177
No matter what level people are in the in the organization,

222
00:15:37,317 --> 00:15:39,859
no one's got an ego, everyone's happy to have a chat.

223
00:15:41,381 --> 00:15:42,181
Everyone's willing to help.

